<div id="review_2637241638" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2637241638" />
    <a title="Ron Christiansen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/2540960-ron-christiansen"><img alt="Ron Christiansen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1298652671p2/2540960.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2637241638?book_show_action=true">Dec 29, 2018</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ron Christiansen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ron Christiansen" href="/user/show/2540960-ron-christiansen">Ron Christiansen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780060923242" href="/book/show/273499.The_Sweet_Hereafter">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2540960-ron-christiansen?shelf=fiction">fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2540960-ron-christiansen?shelf=multiple-narrators">multiple-narrators</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2540960-ron-christiansen?shelf=small-town">small-town</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/2540960-ron-christiansen?shelf=tragedy">tragedy</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2637241638" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7252588544329950790">Sam Dent is a small town where not much happen. This changes in one horrific event. Banks explores how or if we can ascribe blame and if truth can be ascertained. But it is not a philosophical novel. Instead, the exploration plays out through four different viewpoints: the bus driver who is directly involved in the tragedy, a father who loses two children, a lawyer from a big-time firm in New York who believes there are never accidents, and a young middle school girl who was injured in the &quot;acci</span>
  <span id="freeText7252588544329950790" style="display:none">Sam Dent is a small town where not much happen. This changes in one horrific event. Banks explores how or if we can ascribe blame and if truth can be ascertained. But it is not a philosophical novel. Instead, the exploration plays out through four different viewpoints: the bus driver who is directly involved in the tragedy, a father who loses two children, a lawyer from a big-time firm in New York who believes there are never accidents, and a young middle school girl who was injured in the "accident." <br /><br />On finishing, I was compelled to reread the first account of the accident then circle back to some of the lawyer's reasoning. I was left unsure how to feel. It still niggles at me...possibly this is the genius of the novel. There are no clear answers, not just the black and white answers concerning fault and truth but even the more ambiguous questions about how a town survives the loss of children and how a town or an individual should handle tragedy.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7252588544329950790" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


