<div id="review_82837414" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/82837414" />
    <a title="Michael" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/42934-michael"><img alt="Michael" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1452114950p2/42934.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/82837414?book_show_action=true">Jan 01, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael" href="/user/show/42934-michael">Michael</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780060923242" href="/book/show/273499.The_Sweet_Hereafter">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/42934-michael?shelf=literary-novels">literary-novels</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer82837414" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7495430419662680153">Banks&apos;s writing is easy to read. His prose is conversational, and any first person narrator he inhabits sounds real. I believe the voices he uses. I believe them as people. Whether I believe the facts of any of the plots in his books is another question, but one that is rich and interesting to ponder.<br/><br/>Still, the two books of his I&apos;ve read have broken my heart. I&apos;m not running out to the store to buy the rest of his catalog. I&apos;m old and haggard and jaded enough as it is.<br/><br/><i>The Sweet Hereafter</i> gives u</span>
  <span id="freeText7495430419662680153" style="display:none">Banks's writing is easy to read. His prose is conversational, and any first person narrator he inhabits sounds real. I believe the voices he uses. I believe them as people. Whether I believe the facts of any of the plots in his books is another question, but one that is rich and interesting to ponder.<br /><br />Still, the two books of his I've read have broken my heart. I'm not running out to the store to buy the rest of his catalog. I'm old and haggard and jaded enough as it is.<br /><br /><i>The Sweet Hereafter</i> gives us no romantic notions of life in the Adirondacks. It tells us nothing comforting. There are no heroes. And yet, as stark and heavy handed as that sounds, Banks makes it interesting. He gets us through each section, through the stories of four narrators, linked to a school bus accident in a small town, by painting the details of this familiar life with subtlety and skill. Each of these narrators has come to terms with themselves in one way or another, and even Nichole Burnell, the most seemingly pure character in the book, when she speaks the truth, speaks it vindictively.<br /><br />There are mysteries here too, the almost mystical quality of a small dreary town functioning as one moody beast.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7495430419662680153" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


